# Plugin naming rules

When creating or deploying WordPress plugins in this repo, follow these rules so WordPress and installs (zip upload) work correctly.

## Plugin slug

- **Slug** = lowercase, hyphenated identifier (e.g. `knowles-booking`, `knowles-data-dashboard`).
- Use the slug consistently for: deployed folder name, main plugin file name, text domain, script/style handles.

## Deployed folder and main file

- **Installed path:** `wp-content/plugins/<slug>/` (e.g. `wp-content/plugins/knowles-booking/`).
- **Main plugin file:** `<slug>.php` in that folder (e.g. `knowles-booking/knowles-booking.php`).
- WordPress expects to find the main file with the plugin header inside the folder; the **folder name and main file name must match** (both = slug) so that zip install and “Plugin file does not exist” are avoided.

## Installation zip

- **Storage (Knowles project rule):** Installation zips are stored in **`plugins/dist/<slug>/`** (e.g. `plugins/dist/knowles-booking/knowles-booking-1.9.5.zip`), **not** in `plugins/` root or inside each plugin source folder (e.g. not in `plugins/booking/`).
- The zip must have **one top-level folder**, and that folder **must be the plugin slug** (e.g. `knowles-booking`).
- Contents: `knowles-booking/knowles-booking.php`, `knowles-booking/VERSION`, etc.
- Do **not** use a different root folder name (e.g. `booking`) when the main file is `knowles-booking.php`, or WordPress may show “Plugin file does not exist”.
- Build the zip so the root of the zip is `<slug>/` and save the zip to **`plugins/dist/<slug>/<slug>-X.Y.Z.zip`** (see .docs/booking/README.md for the build steps).
- **Always rebuild the zips** after any change that affects a plugin (code, version, naming, assets). Run from project root: `.\scripts\build-booking-zip.ps1` and `.\scripts\build-dashboard-zip.ps1` so deployment packages are up to date before finishing.

## Code conventions (per plugin)

- **Text domain:** Same as slug (e.g. `knowles-booking`). Use in every `__()`, `esc_html__()`, etc.
- **Options / transients:** Prefix with slug using underscores (e.g. `knowles_booking_*`).
- **Constants:** UPPER_SNAKE from slug (e.g. `KNOWLES_BOOKING_VERSION`, `KNOWLES_BOOKING_PATH`).
- **Class prefix:** PascalCase from slug (e.g. `Knowles_Booking_Admin`, `Knowles_Booking_Public`).
- **Plugin header — Plugins list only:** `Plugin Name` must be **`(Chameleon) Display Name`** (prefix first) so all Chameleon products group together on **Plugins → Installed Plugins**. Example: `(Chameleon) Email Send and Log`, `(Chameleon) Knowles Booking`. Put the release number only in **`Version:`** (and `VERSION` file / constants), **not** in `Plugin Name`.
- **Display name everywhere else:** Admin submenu labels, screen titles, notices, and user-facing copy use **Display Name only** (no `(Chameleon)` prefix or suffix). Append **v{version}** on admin screen titles when helpful. Canonical display names: **`.tools/chameleon-plugin-manifest.json`**.
- **Author:** **`Lee Carter`** on every Chameleon plugin header (`Author:` line). `Author URI:` remains https://chameleoncodewing.co.uk.
- **Description:** Short, informative one-line (or two short lines) in the plugin header — what the plugin does and key dependency if non-obvious. Keep in sync with manifest when listed there.
- **Slug / zip / install folder:** Lowercase kebab-case **functional slug** (e.g. `email-send-and-log`, `woo-mailer`, `knowles-booking`). Do **not** add a `chameleon-` prefix to the slug, zip filename, or `wp-content/plugins/<slug>/` folder unless the product slug itself is `chameleon-admin`. WooCommerce plugins use the `woo-` prefix where applicable. Zip: `<slug>-<semver>.zip` inside `dist/<slug>/`.

## WooCommerce-related plugins: use **Woo**, not **WooCommerce**

For Chameleon plugins that integrate with the WooCommerce plugin:

- **Display name:** Use **Woo** (e.g. `Woo Product Search`, `Woo Central Manager Hub`, `Woo Export Import Customer Order Details`). Do **not** spell out **WooCommerce** in display names, admin menu labels, or the Plugins list name (after the `(Chameleon)` prefix).
- **Slug / folder / main file:** Prefer **`woo-`** prefix (e.g. `woo-product-search`, `woo-central-manager-hub`). Do **not** use `woocommerce-` in new slugs or repo install folders.
- **Descriptions:** May say “Woo store”, “Woo products”, or “requires WooCommerce” when the dependency must be explicit; otherwise prefer **Woo**.
- **Code:** Keep `class_exists( 'WooCommerce' )`, `Automattic\WooCommerce\…`, and other **WooCommerce API** identifiers unchanged — only **naming** (slug, folder, display strings) uses **Woo**.

## Multi-plugin layout (this repo)

- Repo paths: `plugins/booking/`, `plugins/dashboard/plugin/` (or similar). The **repo** folder name can differ from the slug (e.g. `booking` in repo).
- When **deploying** (zip or copy), the **installed** folder must be the **plugin slug** (e.g. `knowles-booking`) so that the main file path is `wp-content/plugins/knowles-booking/knowles-booking.php`.

## Checklist

- [ ] Slug is lowercase with hyphens.
- [ ] Main plugin file is `<slug>.php`.
- [ ] Installation zip is saved in **`plugins/dist/<slug>/`** (e.g. `plugins/dist/knowles-booking/knowles-booking-1.9.5.zip`).
- [ ] Installation zip has a single top-level folder named `<slug>`.
- [ ] Text domain = slug.
- [ ] Options/transients use slug with underscores as prefix.
- [ ] Constants and class names use the same slug-derived naming.
- [ ] After plugin changes, rebuild both zips (`build-booking-zip.ps1`, `build-dashboard-zip.ps1`).
- [ ] `Plugin Name` is **`(Chameleon) Display Name`** (list only); admin/UI uses display name without `(Chameleon)`; **`Version:`** holds semver.
- [ ] `Author:` is **Lee Carter**; description is short and informative.
